The Pax Romana was a time of relative peace and stability across the Roman Empire that lasted from 27 B.C. to 180 A.D. It lasted from 27 B.C. to 180 A.D. This order was maintained by a powerful central government, a well-trained and organized military, and a system of laws and institutions that enabled the empire to be efficiently administered. In addition, the Pax Romana was fostered by the construction of a shared culture and language, as well as the development of infrastructure like as roads and communication networks that allowed commerce and the movement of people and products throughout the Roman Empire. The Pax Romana also depended on the Roman Republic and Roman Empire's capacity to acquire and dominate regions and to establish a system of government and administration in those lands, which made it possible to preserve the Pax Romana. 